# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zeek-network-monitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Routers and switches that support NetFlow can collect IP traffic statistics on all interfaces where NetFlow is enabled, and later export those statistics as NetFlow records toward at least one NetFlow collector—typically a server that does the actual traffic analysis.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Note that the Egress interface, IP Nexthop or BGP Nexthops are not part of the key, and may not be accurate if the route changes before the expiration of the flow, or if load-balancing is done per-packet.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This definition of flows is also used for IPv6, and a similar definition is used for MPLS and Ethernet flows.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Advanced NetFlow or IPFIX implementations like Cisco Flexible NetFlow allow user-defined flow keys.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The router will output a flow record when it determines that the flow is finished.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] It does this by flow aging: when the router sees new traffic for an existing flow it resets the aging counter.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Also, TCP session termination in a TCP flow causes the router to expire the flow.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Routers can also be configured to output a flow record at a fixed interval even if the flow is still ongoing.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow records are traditionally exported using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and collected using a NetFlow collector.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The IP address of the NetFlow collector and the destination UDP port must be configured on the sending router.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] A common value is UDP port 2055, but other values like 9555 or 9995, 9025, 9026 etc. can also be used.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] For efficiency reasons, the router traditionally does not keep track of flow records already exported, so if a NetFlow packet is dropped due to network congestion or packet corruption, all contained records are lost forever.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The UDP protocol does not inform the router of the loss so it can send the packets again.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This can be a real problem, especially with NetFlow v8 or v9 that can aggregate a lot of packets or flows into a single record.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] A single UDP packet loss can cause a huge impact on the statistics of some flows.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] That is why some modern implementations of NetFlow use the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) to export packets so as to provide some protection against packet loss, and make sure that NetFlow v9 templates are received before any related record is exported.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Note that TCP would not be suitable for NetFlow because a strict ordering of packets would cause excessive buffering and delays.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The problem with SCTP is that it requires interaction between each NetFlow collector and each router exporting NetFlow.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] There may be performance limitations if a router has to deal with many NetFlow collectors, and a NetFlow collector has to deal with many routers, especially when some of them are unavailable due to failure or maintenance.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] SCTP may not be efficient if NetFlow must be exported toward several independent collectors, some of which may be test servers that can go down at any moment.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] UDP allows simple replication of NetFlow packets using Network taps or L2 or L3 Mirroring.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Simple stateless equipment can also filter or change the destination address of NetFlow UDP packets if necessary.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Since NetFlow export almost only use network backbone links, packet loss will often be negligible.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] If it happens, it will mostly be on the link between the network and the NetFlow collectors.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] A NetFlow record can contain a wide variety of information about the traffic in a given flow.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] For ICMP flows, the Source Port is zero, and the Destination Port number field codes ICMP message Type and Code (port = ICMP-Type * 256 + ICMP-Code) .
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The source and destination Autonomous System (AS) number fields can report the destination AS (last AS of AS-Path) or the immediate neighbor AS (first AS of AS-Path) depending on the router configuration.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] But the AS number will be zero if the feature is not supported, the route is unknown or not announced by BGP, or the AS is the local AS.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] There is no explicit way to distinguish between these cases.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] By analyzing flow data, a picture of traffic flow and traffic volume in a network can be built.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The NetFlow record format has evolved over time, hence the inclusion of version numbers.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Cisco maintains details of the different version numbers and the layout of the packets for each version.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow is usually enabled on a per-interface basis to limit load on the router components involved in NetFlow, or to limit the amount of NetFlow records exported.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow usually captures all packets received by an ingress IP interface, but some NetFlow implementations use IP filters to decide if a packet can be observed by NetFlow.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Some NetFlow implementations also allow the observation of packets on the egress IP interface, but this must be used with care: all flows from any ingress interface with NetFlow enabled to any interface with NetFlow enabled could be counted twice.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Standard NetFlow was designed to process all IP packets on an interface.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] But in some environments, e.g. on Internet backbones, that was too costly, due to the extra processing required for each packet, and large number of simultaneous flows.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] So Cisco introduced sampled NetFlow on Cisco 12000, and that is now used in all high-end routers that implement NetFlow.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Only one packet out of *n* is processed, where *n*, the sampling rate, is determined by the router configuration.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Some implementations have more complex methods to sample packets, like per-flow sampling on Cisco Catalysts.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The sampling rate is often the same for all interfaces, but can be adjusted per interface for some routers.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] When Sampled NetFlow is used, the NetFlow records must be adjusted for the effect of sampling - traffic volumes, in particular, are now an estimate rather than the actual measured flow volume.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow was initially implemented by Cisco, and described in an "informational" document that was not on the standards track: RFC 3954 – Cisco Systems NetFlow Services Export Version 9.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The NetFlow protocol itself has been superseded by Internet Protocol Flow Information eXport (IPFIX).
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Based on the NetFlow Version 9 implementation, IPFIX is on the IETF standards track with RFC 5101 (obsoleted by RFC 7011), RFC 5102 (obsoleted by RFC 7012), etc. which were published in 2008.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Many vendors other than Cisco provide similar network flow monitoring technology.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow may be a prevalent name in the area of flow monitoring, because of Cisco dominant market share in the networking industry.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Also flow-tools collection of software allows to process and manage NetFlow exports from Cisco and Juniper routers.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Introduced with the launch of the Cisco ASA 5580 products, NetFlow Security Event Logging utilizes NetFlow v9 fields and templates in order to efficiently deliver security telemetry in high performance environments.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow Security Event Logging scales better than syslog while offering the same level of detail and granularity in logged events.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow collection using standalone NetFlow probes is an alternative to flow collection from routers and switches.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This approach can overcome some limitations of router-based NetFlow monitoring.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The probes are transparently connected to the monitored link as a passive appliance using the TAP or SPAN port of the appliance.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Historically, NetFlow monitoring is easier to implement in a dedicated probe than in a router.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The easiest way to address the above drawbacks is to use a packet capture appliance inline in front of the router and capture all of the NetFlow output from the router.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This method allows for storage of large amount of NetFlow data (typically many years worth of data) and does not require reconfiguration of the network.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow collection from dedicated probes is well suited for observation of critical links, whereas NetFlow on routers provides a Network-wide view of the traffic that can be used for capacity planning, accounting, performance monitoring, and security.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] NetFlow was originally a Cisco packet switching technology for Cisco routers, implemented in IOS 11.x around 1996.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] It was originally a software implementation for the Cisco 7000, 7200 and 7500, where it was thought as an improvement over the then current Cisco Fast Switching.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Netflow was invented by Darren Kerr and Barry Bruin from Cisco (U.S. patent # 6,243,667 ).
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The idea was that the first packet of a flow would create a NetFlow switching record.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This record would then be used for all later packets of the same flow, until the expiration of the flow.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] Only the first packet of a flow would require an investigation of the route table to find the most specific matching route.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This is an expensive operation in software implementations, especially the old ones without Forwarding information base.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] The NetFlow switching record was actually some kind of route cache record, and old versions of IOS still refer to the NetFlow cache as **ip route-cache**.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This technology was advantageous for local networks.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This was especially true if some of the traffic had to be filtered by an ACL as only the first packet of a flow had to be evaluated by the ACL.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] As a switching technology, NetFlow was replaced around 1995 by Cisco Express Forwarding.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] This first appeared on Cisco 12000 routers, and later replaced NetFlow switching on advanced IOS for the Cisco 7200 and Cisco 7500.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] As of 2012, technologies similar to NetFlow switching are still in use in most firewalls and software-based IP routers.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/netflow] For instance the conntrack feature of the Netfilter framework used by Linux.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] While an intrusion detection system monitors network threats from the outside, a network monitoring system monitors the network for problems caused by overloaded or crashed servers, network connections or other devices.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] For example, to determine the status of a web server, monitoring software may periodically send an HTTP request to fetch a page.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] For email servers, a test message might be sent through SMTP and retrieved by IMAP or POP3.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Commonly measured metrics are response time, availability and uptime, although both consistency and reliability metrics are starting to gain popularity.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] The widespread addition of WAN optimization devices is having an adverse effect on most network monitoring tools, especially when it comes to measuring accurate end-to-end delay because they limit round-trip delay time visibility.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Status request failures, such as when a connection cannot be established, it times-out, or the document or message cannot be retrieved, usually produce an action from the monitoring system.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] These actions vary; An alarm may be sent (via SMS, email, etc.) to the resident sysadmin, automatic failover systems may be activated to remove the troubled server from duty until it can be repaired, etc.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Monitoring the performance of a network uplink is also known as network traffic measurement.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Network tomography is an important area of network measurement, which deals with monitoring the health of various links in a network using end-to-end probes sent by agents located at vantage points in the network/Internet.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Route analytics is another important area of network measurement.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] It includes the methods, systems, algorithms and tools to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation or downtime.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Site monitoring services can check HTTP pages, HTTPS, SNMP, FTP, SMTP, POP3, IMAP, DNS, SSH, TELNET, SSL, TCP, ICMP, SIP, UDP, Media Streaming and a range of other ports with a variety of check intervals ranging from every four hours to every one minute.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Typically, most network monitoring services test your server anywhere between once per hour to once per minute.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] For monitoring network performance, most tools use protocols like SNMP, NetFlow, Packet Sniffing, or WMI.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Monitoring an internet server means that the server owner always knows if one or all of their services go down.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Server monitoring may be **internal**, i.e. web server software checks its status and notifies the owner if some services go down, and **external**, i.e. some web server monitoring companies check the status of the services with a certain frequency.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Server monitoring can encompass a check of system metrics, such as CPU usage, memory usage, network performance and disk space.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] It can also include application monitoring, such as checking the processes of programs such as Apache HTTP server, MySQL, Nginx, Postgres and others.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] External monitoring is more reliable, as it keeps on working when the server completely goes down.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Good server monitoring tools also have performance benchmarking, alerting capabilities and the ability to link certain thresholds with automated server jobs, such as provisioning more memory or performing a backup.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Network monitoring services usually have several servers around the globe - for example in America, Europe, Asia, Australia and other locations.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] By having multiple servers in different geographic locations, a monitoring service can determine if a Web server is available across different networks worldwide.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] The more the locations used, the more complete the picture of network availability.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] When monitoring a web server for potential problems, an external web monitoring service checks several parameters.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] First of all, it monitors for a proper HTTP return code.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] By HTTP specifications RFC 2616, any web server returns several HTTP codes.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Analysis of the HTTP codes is the fastest way to determine the current status of the monitored web server.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Third-party application performance monitoring tools provide additional web server monitoring, alerting and reporting capabilities.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] As the information brought by web server monitoring services is in most cases urgent and may be of crucial importance, various notification methods may be used: e-mail, landline and cell phones, messengers, SMS, fax, pagers, etc.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] Network monitoring plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements across multiple industries.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would mandate continuous monitoring of all information systems containing ePHI, including deployment of technology assets that can detect and respond to threats in real time.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires organizations to track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data (Requirement 10), including the use of network monitoring tools to detect unauthorized wireless access points.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/network-monitoring] For U.S. federal agencies, NIST Special Publication 800-53 mandates continuous monitoring under the CA-7 control family as part of the Risk Management Framework.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] A **packet analyzer** (also **packet sniffer** or **network analyzer**) is a computer program or computer hardware such as a packet capture appliance that can analyze and log traffic that passes over a computer network or part of a network.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] **Packet capture** is the process of intercepting and logging traffic.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] As data streams flow across the network, the analyzer captures each packet and, if needed, decodes the packet's raw data, showing the values of various fields in the packet, and analyzes its content according to the appropriate RFC or other specifications.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] A packet analyzer used for intercepting traffic on wireless networks is known as a **wireless analyzer**—those designed specifically for Wi-Fi networks are **Wi-Fi analyzers**.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] While a packet analyzer can also be referred to as a network analyzer or protocol analyzer, these terms can also have other meanings.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] The class of protocol analyzers can technically be a broader, more general class that includes packet analyzers and sniffers.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] However, the terms are frequently used interchangeably.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] On wired shared-medium networks, such as Ethernet, Token Ring, and FDDI, depending on the network structure (hub or switch), it may be possible to capture all traffic on the network from a single machine.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] On modern networks, traffic can be captured using a network switch using port mirroring, which mirrors all packets that pass through designated ports of the switch to another port, if the switch supports port mirroring.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] A network tap is an even more reliable solution than using a monitoring port since taps are less likely to drop packets during high traffic loads.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, traffic can be captured on one channel at a time, or by using multiple adapters, on several channels simultaneously.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] On wired broadcast and wireless LANs, to capture unicast traffic between other machines, the network adapter capturing the traffic must be in promiscuous mode.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, even if the adapter is in promiscuous mode, packets not for the service set the adapter is configured for are usually ignored.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] To see those packets, the adapter must be in monitor mode.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] No special provisions are required to capture multicast traffic to a multicast group the packet analyzer is already monitoring, or broadcast traffic.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] When traffic is captured, either the entire contents of packets or just the headers are recorded.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Recording just headers reduces storage requirements and avoids some privacy legal issues, yet often provides sufficient information to diagnose problems.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Captured information is decoded from raw digital form into a human-readable format that lets engineers review exchanged information.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers vary in their abilities to display and analyze data.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Some packet analyzers can also generate traffic.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Such testers generate protocol-correct traffic for functional testing, and may also have the ability to deliberately introduce errors to test the device under test's ability to handle errors.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers can also be hardware-based, either in probe format or, as is increasingly common, combined with a disk array.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] These devices record packets or packet headers to a disk array.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Packet capture can be used to fulfill a warrant from a law enforcement agency to wiretap all network traffic generated by an individual.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Internet service providers and VoIP providers in the United States must comply with Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act regulations.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Using packet capture and storage, telecommunications carriers can provide the legally required secure and separate access to targeted network traffic and can use the same device for internal security purposes.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] Collecting data from a carrier system without a warrant is illegal due to laws about interception.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/packet-analyzer] By using end-to-end encryption, communications can be kept confidential from telecommunication carriers and legal authorities.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis tasks may be supported by dedicated computer software programs.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Advanced traffic analysis techniques which may include various forms of social network analysis.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis method can be used to break the anonymity of anonymous networks, e.g., TORs.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] There are two methods of traffic-analysis attack, passive and active.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] In a military context, traffic analysis is a basic part of signals intelligence, and can be a source of information about the intentions and actions of the target.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] There is a close relationship between traffic analysis and cryptanalysis (commonly called codebreaking).
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Callsigns and addresses are frequently encrypted, requiring assistance in identifying them.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic volume can often be a sign of an addressee's importance, giving hints to pending objectives or movements to cryptanalysts.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic-flow security is one aspect of communications security.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] The "Communications' metadata intelligence" or "COMINT metadata" is a term in communications intelligence (COMINT) referring to the concept of producing intelligence by analyzing only the technical metadata, hence, is a great practical example for traffic analysis in intelligence.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] While traditionally information gathering in COMINT is derived from intercepting transmissions, tapping the target's communications and monitoring the content of conversations, the metadata intelligence is not based on content but on technical communicational data.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Non-content COMINT is usually used to deduce information about the user of a certain transmitter, such as locations, contacts, activity volume, routine and its exceptions.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] For example, if an emitter is known as the radio transmitter of a certain unit, and by using direction finding (DF) tools, the position of the emitter is locatable, the change of locations from one point to another can be deduced, without listening to any orders or reports.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] If one unit reports back to a command on a certain pattern, and another unit reports on the same pattern to the same command, the two units are probably related.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] That conclusion is based on the metadata of the two units' transmissions, not on the content of their transmissions.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Using all or as much of the metadata available is commonly used to build up an Electronic Order of Battle (EOB) by mapping different entities in the battlefield and their connections.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Of course, the EOB could be built by tapping all the conversations and trying to understand, which unit is where, but using the metadata with an automatic analysis tool enables a much faster and accurate EOB build-up, which, alongside tapping, builds a much better and complete picture.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Similarly to the military aspects, commercial business relationships can also be vulnerable to traffic analysis.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] While the data exchanged will generally be encrypted, the mere flow of data can be informative.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] The rise in multi-party data communications using technologies such as Dataspaces has highlighted this risk once again.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] All of this can provide valuable intelligence for stock traders, competitors, and other business associates.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis is also a concern in computer security.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] An attacker can gain important information by monitoring the frequency and timing of network packets.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] A timing attack on the SSH protocol can use timing information to deduce information about passwords since, during interactive session, SSH transmits each keystroke as a message.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] The time between keystroke messages can be studied using hidden Markov models.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Song, *et al.* claim that it can recover the password fifty times faster than a brute force attack.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Onion routing systems are used to gain anonymity.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis can be used to attack anonymous communication systems like the Tor anonymity network.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Adam Back, Ulf Möeller and Anton Stiglic present traffic analysis attacks against anonymity providing systems.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Murdoch and George Danezis from University of Cambridge presented research showing that traffic-analysis allows adversaries to infer which nodes relay the anonymous streams.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] This reduces the anonymity provided by Tor.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] They have shown that otherwise unrelated streams can be linked back to the same initiator.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Remailer systems can also be attacked via traffic analysis.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] If a message is observed going to a remailing server, and an identical-length (if now anonymized) message is seen exiting the server soon after, a traffic analyst may be able to (automatically) connect the sender with the ultimate receiver.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Variations of remailer operations exist that can make traffic analysis less effective.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis involves intercepting and scrutinizing cybersecurity threats to gather valuable insights about anonymous data flowing through the exit node.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] By using technique rooted in dark web crawling and specializing software, one can identify the specific characteristics of a client's network traffic within the dark web.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] It is difficult to defeat traffic analysis without both encrypting messages and masking the channel.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] When no actual messages are being sent, the channel can be *masked* by sending dummy traffic, similar to the encrypted traffic, thereby keeping bandwidth usage constant.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] "It is very hard to hide information about the size or timing of messages.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] Even for Internet access, where there is not a per-packet charge, Internet service providers (ISPs) make the statistical assumption that connections from user sites will not be busy 100% of the time.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] The user cannot simply increase the bandwidth of the link, since masking would fill that as well.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/traffic-analysis] If masking, which often can be built into end-to-end encryptors, becomes common practice, ISPs will have to change their traffic assumptions.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark is cross-platform, using the Qt widget toolkit in current releases to implement its user interface, and using pcap to capture packets; it runs on Linux, macOS, BSD, Solaris, some other Unix-like operating systems, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] There is also a terminal-based (non-GUI) version called TShark.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark, and the other programs distributed with it such as TShark, are free software, released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 or any later version.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark is very similar to tcpdump, but has a graphical front-end and integrated sorting and filtering options.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark is also widely used in cybersecurity to detect suspicious network activity, including packet sniffing and intrusion attempts.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark lets the user put network interface controllers into promiscuous mode and is commonly used in ethical hacking and network security analysis.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] (if supported by the network interface controller), so they can see all the traffic visible on that interface including unicast traffic not sent to that network interface controller's MAC address.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] However, when capturing with a packet analyzer in promiscuous mode on a port on a network switch, not all traffic through the switch is necessarily sent to the port where the capture is done, so capturing in promiscuous mode is not necessarily sufficient to see all network traffic.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Port mirroring or various network taps extend capture to any point on the network.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Simple passive taps are extremely resistant to tampering.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] On Linux, BSD, and macOS, with libpcap 1.0.0 or later, Wireshark 1.4 and later can also put wireless network interface controllers into monitor mode.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] If a remote machine captures packets and sends the captured packets to a machine running Wireshark using the TZSP protocol or the protocol used by OmniPeek, Wireshark dissects those packets, so it can analyze packets captured on a remote machine at the time that they are captured.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] In the late 1990s, Gerald Combs, a computer science graduate of the University of Missouri–Kansas City, was working for a small Internet service provider, Network Integration Services.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] The commercial protocol analysis products at the time were priced around $1500 and did not run on the company's primary platforms (Solaris and Linux), so Gerald began writing Ethereal and released the first version around 1998.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] The Ethereal trademark is owned by Network Integration Services.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] In May 2006, Combs accepted a job with CACE Technologies with Loris Degioanni.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Combs still held copyright on most of Ethereal's source code (and the rest was re-distributable under the GNU GPL), so he used the contents of the Ethereal Subversion repository as the basis for the Wireshark repository.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] However, he did not own the Ethereal trademark, so he changed the name to Wireshark.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] In 2010 Riverbed Technology purchased CACE and took over as the primary sponsor of Wireshark.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Ethereal development has ceased, and an Ethereal security advisory recommended switching to Wireshark.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] In 2022, Sysdig took over as the primary sponsor of Wireshark, and, in 2023, established the Wireshark Foundation and put Wireshark into that foundation.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark has won several industry awards over the years, including *eWeek*, *InfoWorld*, and *PC Magazine*.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] It is also the top-rated packet sniffer in the Insecure.Org network security tools survey and was the SourceForge Project of the Month in August 2010.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Combs continues to maintain the overall code of Wireshark and to issue releases of new versions of the software.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] The product website lists more than 2000 contributing authors.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark is a data capturing program that "understands" the structure (encapsulation) of different networking protocols.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] It can parse and display the fields, along with their meanings as specified by different networking protocols.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark uses pcap to capture packets, so it can only capture packets on the types of networks that pcap supports.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] It can also read captures from other network analyzers, such as snoop, Network General's Sniffer, and Microsoft Network Monitor.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Capturing raw network traffic from an interface typically requires elevated privileges on many platforms.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark can also be used to analyze network traffic in cybersecurity research, including simulated attack traffic.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] For this reason, older versions of Wireshark and TShark were often run with superuser permissions to access network interfaces directly.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Considering the huge number of protocol dissectors that are called when traffic is captured and recognizing the possibility of a bug in a dissector, a serious security risk can be posed.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Due to the rather large number of vulnerabilities in the past (of which many have allowed remote code execution) and developers' doubts for better future development, OpenBSD removed Ethereal from its ports tree prior to OpenBSD 3.6.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Elevated privileges are not needed for all operations.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] For example, an alternative is to run tcpdump or the *dumpcap* utility that comes with Wireshark with superuser privileges to capture packets into a file, and later analyze the packets by running Wireshark with restricted privileges.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] To emulate near realtime analysis, each captured file may be merged by *mergecap* into a growing file processed by Wireshark.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] On wireless networks, it is possible to use the Aircrack wireless security tools to capture IEEE 802.11 frames and read the resulting dump files with Wireshark.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] As of Wireshark 0.99.7, Wireshark and TShark run dumpcap to perform traffic capture.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Platforms that require special privileges to capture traffic need only arrange that dumpcap is run with those privileges.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Neither Wireshark nor TShark need to or should be run with special privileges.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark can color packets based on rules that match particular fields in packets, to help the user identify the types of traffic at a glance.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] A default set of rules is provided; users can change existing rules for coloring packets, add new rules, or remove rules.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/wireshark] Wireshark can also be used to capture packets from most network simulation tools such as ns and OPNET Modeler.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Zeek's purpose is to inspect network traffic and generate a variety of logs describing the activity it sees.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] A complete list of log files is available at the project documentation site.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] One of Zeek's primary use cases involves cyber threat hunting.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] The principal author, Paxson, originally named the software "Bro" as a warning regarding George Orwell's Big Brother from the novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] In 2018 the project leadership team decided to rename the software.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] At LBNL in the 1990s, the developers ran their sensors as a pseudo-user named "zeek", thereby inspiring the name change in 2018.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Security teams identify locations on their network where they desire visibility.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] They deploy one or more network taps or enable switch SPAN ports for port mirroring to gain access to traffic.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] They deploy Zeek on servers with access to those visibility points.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] The Zeek software on the server deciphers network traffic as logs, writing them to local disk or remote storage.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Zeek's event engine analyzes live or recorded network traffic to generate neutral event logs.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Zeek uses common ports and dynamic protocol detection (involving signatures as well as behavioral analysis) to identify network protocols.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Developers write Zeek policy scripts in the Turing complete Zeek scripting language.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] By default Zeek logs information about events to files, but analysts can also configure Zeek to take other actions, such as sending an email, raising an alert, executing a system command, updating an internal metric, or calling another Zeek script.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Zeek analyzers perform application layer decoding, anomaly detection, signature matching and connection analysis.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] Zeek's developers designed the software to incorporate additional analyzers.
[src:zeek-network-monitor/zeek] The latest method for creating new protocol analyzers relies on the Spicy framework.
